subject: Fix QTest not failing on fatal signals in android

messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

I have doubts about the wisdom of stomping Android's signal handlers.

Patch Set 2: Sanity-Review-1

(1 comment)

See http://wiki.qt.io/Early_Warning_System for explanations.
Patch Set 3: Published edit on patch set 2.

Patch Set 4:

(3 comments)

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> (2 comments)
> 
> I have doubts about the wisdom of stomping Android's signal handlers.

The Android signal handlers cannot be overwritten. Android implemented a "sigchain", which acts as a interception layer and makes user code signal handlers to be ran only after Android ART signal handlers.

Patch Set 4:

(4 comments)

> Patch Set 4:
> 
> (3 comments)
> 
> > Patch Set 1:
> > 
> > (2 comments)
> > 
> > I have doubts about the wisdom of stomping Android's signal handlers.
> 
> The Android signal handlers cannot be overwritten. Android implemented a "sigchain", which acts as a interception layer and makes user code signal handlers to be ran only after Android ART signal handlers.

Does that mean the attempt to remove the signal handler we add is also prevented from happening ?
If so, see comments on the destructor and signal().
Or do user code signal handlers still work as normal on other Linux variants ?
In that case, the prior code would restore a handler that a client of testlib has installed; which I suppose is what it's really there for; but now it will stomp it.

Does Android provide any way to detect that the handler we get back from sigaction() is an Android ART handler, rather than a user-space handler that we would be overriding ?
Patch Set 5: Commit message was updated.

Patch Set 6:

> Patch Set 4:
> 
> (4 comments)
> 
> > Patch Set 4:
> > 
> > (3 comments)
> > 
> > > Patch Set 1:
> > > 
> > > (2 comments)
> > > 
> > > I have doubts about the wisdom of stomping Android's signal handlers.
> > 
> > The Android signal handlers cannot be overwritten. Android implemented a "sigchain", which acts as a interception layer and makes user code signal handlers to be ran only after Android ART signal handlers.
> 
> Does that mean the attempt to remove the signal handler we add is also prevented from happening ?
> If so, see comments on the destructor and signal().
> Or do user code signal handlers still work as normal on other Linux variants ?
> In that case, the prior code would restore a handler that a client of testlib has installed; which I suppose is what it's really there for; but now it will stomp it.
> 
> Does Android provide any way to detect that the handler we get back from sigaction() is an Android ART handler, rather than a user-space handler that we would be overriding ?

There is almost no documentation on how that works, except by reading the source code. But, I was able to figure out is that user code signals work like other Linux variants. 

This implementation only "chains" and runs "special handlers" made by ART. Those cannot be removed and are run first.
The "user code" handlers are not chained, and there is just one at a time. So sigaction will remove the previous "user code" handler, which means that is no need to make a special case for removing those handlers on android

Patch Set 6:

(2 comments)

> Patch Set 6:
>
> This implementation only "chains" and runs "special handlers" made by ART. Those cannot be removed and are run first.

In which case it probably shouldn't be returning the "special handlers" in the sigaction API.
Or they should be returning SIG_DFL to indicate that the "default" handler is *all* that's being run.

> The "user code" handlers are not chained, and there is just one at a time. So sigaction will remove the previous "user code" handler, which means that is no need to make a special case for removing those handlers on android

The code you're changing is *restoring* the user-code handler if it finds one; your change breaks that.
The problem you're trying to solve is that Android's special signal handlers - that it calls in any case, whether the user-space program sets one or not - are reported as if they were user-space signal handlers (that get displaced by sigaction() when we install our replacement), when they're not actually displaced by ours, so the existing code is mislead into thinking there's a user-space handler installed already.

So while the change to check the return from sigaction() is good (and could indeed be broken out as a separate uncontentios fix), what you're doing - to work round Android's misguided reporting of its special handlers as if they were user-space - is problematic.
What we really need here is some way to distinguish Android's chained "special" handlers from real user-space handlers that we might be displacing; the latter we want to restore, the former we can cheerfully treat as SIG_DFL.

Patch Set 6:

This may make the situation a little clearer:
https://codereview.qt-project.org/c/qt/qtbase/+/381577

>

> 
> So while the change to check the return from sigaction() is good (and could indeed be broken out as a separate uncontentios fix), what you're doing - to work round Android's misguided reporting of its special handlers as if they were user-space - is problematic.
> What we really need here is some way to distinguish Android's chained "special" handlers from real user-space handlers that we might be displacing; the latter we want to restore, the former we can cheerfully treat as SIG_DFL.

The problem I am trying to solve is that qtestlib doesn't catch signals on android. So if a test crashes, the execution stops but qtestlib returns have the test has passed.

Not only "special handlers" sigactions are being added in ART runtime. Check in here : https://cs.android.com/android/platform/superproject/+/master:art/runtime/runtime_common.cc;l=521;drc=master on the InitPlatformSignalHandlersCommon function.

These sigactions are not SIG_DFL and I did not find a reliable way to check if those functions are added by Android ART. 

So the behavior that it should restore the user-code handler if it finds one does not work well with android and that is why I disabled it. 

An alternative is to simply run both handlers, ours and the previous one, it would work for every case. I will push here code for this but is quite a bit of refactoring. It was tested on Android and macOs.

Patch Set 4:

After using the new query command to implement the deploy-one-QML-module command in the next commit in the series, I've tweaked the keywords here and what they mean to better fit how you'd typically need to use the command. An important aspect that came out of that is that we still want the project to install/deploy the backing target and plugin target, otherwise CMake doesn't get a chance to rewrite RPATH information. This is actually pretty consistent with what we do for deploying apps too, we just haven't been particularly explicit about that in the docs for those earlier deployment-related commands.

messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

This change is ready for review.

Patch Set 1:

I would like a textual description of what the default/recommended/possible install locations are for the different bundling/installation/deployment scenarios on the different platforms. It's hard to see from the code.

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> I would like a textual description of what the default/recommended/possible install locations are for the different bundling/installation/deployment scenarios on the different platforms. It's hard to see from the code.

For a macOS app bundle, we install to the base of the install location and we follow the prescribed bundle layout dictated by Apple. It would be unusual to do anything else for that specific scenario. For all other cases, we follow the standard CMake install layout, which typically looks like this:

* Executables go in "bin"
* On Windows, DLLs go in "bin"
* On non-Windows, shared libraries go in "lib", although Linux distributions often use an architecture-specific directory instead, or a subdirectory below "lib". CMake abstracts those away for us when we include the GNUInstallDirs module.

We also establish the convention that "qml" is the location under which we put all our QML modules. That's already what Qt itself does. Makes sense to do that for user projects too. Ultimately, we probably want to allow user projects to customise that, but I haven't documented or possibly fully implemented that yet.

Patch Set 2:

> We also establish the convention that "qml" is the location under which we put all our QML modules. That's already what Qt itself does. Makes sense to do that for user projects too. Ultimately, we probably want to allow user projects to customise that, but I haven't documented or possibly fully implemented that yet.

This means that we should probably add this "qml" directory to the default import path. I guess we expect or generate a qt.conf file in every app bundle, though?

Patch Set 2:

How will this work for the other bundle formats? ios, android? Maybe self contained applications on linux, installed into /opt
Uploaded patch set 4: Patch Set 3 was rebased.

Patch Set 6:

This change is ready for review.

Patch Set 6:

> Patch Set 2:
> 
> > We also establish the convention that "qml" is the location under which we put all our QML modules. That's already what Qt itself does. Makes sense to do that for user projects too. Ultimately, we probably want to allow user projects to customise that, but I haven't documented or possibly fully implemented that yet.
> 
> This means that we should probably add this "qml" directory to the default import path. I guess we expect or generate a qt.conf file in every app bundle, though?

We do for macOS app bundles (macdeployqt always writes one). We would need a qt.conf file on Windows if the app follows CMake's default install layout. The qt_generate_deploy_app_script () and qt_generate_deploy_qml_app_script() commands write a qt.conf file on Windows too. For everywhere else, projects will have to decide if a qt.conf file is needed or not.

Patch Set 6:

> Patch Set 2:
> 
> How will this work for the other bundle formats? ios, android? Maybe self contained applications on linux, installed into /opt


For iOS we only support static Qt, for which none of the new deployment-related support is relevant (it is only for use with non-static Qt).

Android is handled specially as build steps. We discussed at this week's CMake team meeting about whether moving it to the install step would make sense. I think the plan is to stick with the build-time approach Alexey has been working on for the moment. I developed the deployment API with the possibility of adding android later in mind though, so we haven't locked ourselves out of doing that in a future release.

On Linux, we don't have a deploy tool like macdeployqt or windeplotqt. If we wanted to support Linux for runtime dependencies, I'd suggest we look at a CMake-based implementation using file(GET_RUNTIME_DEPENDENCIES), since then you'd have an implementation that could theoretically work on any non-cross-compiled platform, not just Linux. That may be more maintainable in the next major Qt release, years from now, but the existing standalone deploy tools would probably still need to be retained to keep other build systems supported.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Build or autotests failed.
- failure: macOS Latest Clang (https://github.com/cristianadam/qt-creator/runs/4461213774?check_suite_focus=true)
- failure: Ubuntu Latest GCC (https://github.com/cristianadam/qt-creator/runs/4461213706?check_suite_focus=true)
- failure: Windows Latest MinGW (https://github.com/cristianadam/qt-creator/runs/4461213631?check_suite_focus=true)
- failure: Windows Latest MSVC (https://github.com/cristianadam/qt-creator/runs/4461213562?check_suite_focus=true)

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Usually when the github-actions-qt-creator bot fails for all four jobs it signals that there is an error.

I tried it locally and got:

CMake Error at C:/Qt/6.2.1/msvc2019_64/lib/cmake/Qt6Core/Qt6CoreMacros.cmake:1147 (message):
  Metatype generation requires either the use of AUTOMOC or a manual list of
  generated json files
Call Stack (most recent call first):
  C:/Qt/6.2.1/msvc2019_64/lib/cmake/Qt6Core/Qt6CoreMacros.cmake:1260 (qt6_extract_metatypes)
  cmake/QtCreatorAPI.cmake:313 (qt_extract_metatypes)
  src/libs/sqlite/CMakeLists.txt:1 (add_qtc_library)

which was more helpful than the error on GitHub Actions.

With the following update:

  get_target_property(have_automoc_prop ${name} AUTOMOC)
  if(${Qt5_VERSION} VERSION_GREATER_EQUAL "6.2.0" AND "${have_automoc_prop}")
    qt_extract_metatypes(${name})
  endif()

The configuration and compilation was fine.

messages.message:
Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2 Sanity-Review+1

Apparently pushing a Work In Progress

Patch Set 1:

What do you think? This is because on Android emulated tests, my TESTRUNNER wrapper receives as final arguments, a full command line of 

    androidtestrunner androidtestrunner --path ... --adb ... ...

and it tries to interpret these long options unsuccessfully.

The disadvantage of this patch is that it requires that all TESTRUNNER wrapper scripts understand "--". If this is not desirable I could try to change my wrapper script to stop parsing any argument after the 1st positional argument. But I haven't figure out a way to do that yet using python's argparse.

Patch Set 1:

I think looking for a different way would be better. TESTRUNNER can be any arbitrary script after all.

Worst case scenario, you could perhaps set some internal env variable, and modify the cmake build system code to add the -- separator then.

Patch Set 1:

>  set some internal env variable
But that will certainly confuse/anger developers more when they try to repro the script running locally and have to hunt for an env var that is set in the CI but not locally

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> What do you think? This is because on Android emulated tests, my TESTRUNNER wrapper receives as final arguments, a full command line of 
> 
>     androidtestrunner androidtestrunner --path ... --adb ... ...
> 
> and it tries to interpret these long options unsuccessfully.
> 
> The disadvantage of this patch is that it requires that all TESTRUNNER wrapper scripts understand "--". If this is not desirable I could try to change my wrapper script to stop parsing any argument after the 1st positional argument. But I haven't figure out a way to do that yet using python's argparse.

I'm wondering if setting TESTRUNNER="/path/to/pythonscript.py;--script_arg1;--script_arg2;--" will work in this case.

messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

straw-man patch based on Uwe's suggestion

Patch Set 1:

An alternative would be to bring that containsMode enum up to QQuickItem and add a MaskContains enum value, which will mean use this behavior instead of bounding box.

Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

Seems like a reasonable behavior change to me. Would be nice to have a test for it.

Patch Set 3:

clipRect is currently \internal. I don't think we should do this (or at least, not ChangeLog it) without documenting and publicizing what we want clipRect to actually be used for.

Patch Set 3:

I'm not sure either... but you should read QTBUG-65741

Patch Set 3:

but maybe one of the main cases that will matter is when a Shape with a PathSvg, PathCubic, ... has parts which go far outside the bounds of the Shape.  (Because SVG has absolute rather than relative coordinates, this happens easily when you try to import a drawing into QML by cut-and-pasting the paths from an SVG file, or some such.)  You might turn on clipping... but contains() will check all the paths anyway, if containsMode is set to FillContains.  So at the very least it seems there ought to be another containsMode, or we could turn it into a Q_FLAGS so that you could OR them together, but ORing the flags would mean ANDing the rules (if containsMode: BoundingRectContains | FillContains, then we will check both at runtime).  Maybe that's confusing... so we could alternatively add ClippedFillContains I guess.

If we eventually find a way to efficiently use a Shape or Path as a clip, we'll have to think some more what to do about the hit testing, so shouldn't do anything API-wise which will cause trouble then.

Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

imo this makes sense, and doing as Michael suggests, meaning better documenting the behavior, could be sufficient

Patch Set 3:

What is the difference between clipRect and boundingRect anyway? It's all very fuzzy to me.
The result of boundingRect() seems to be used very little.
(Found a usage in qtquickcontrols and some usages in qtlocation, but maybe clipRect() would have been sufficient (and more correct) for those)

Patch Set 3:

I agree that it doesn't necessarily make sense without adding documentation about which rect to use for which purpose.  So we have to make up our minds somehow.

Patch Set 3:

Removing myself to clean up my dashboard. If needed, add me back when work continues. Thanks!

Removed reviewer Richard Moe Gustavsen with the following votes:

* Code-Review+1 by Richard Moe Gustavsen <richard.gustavsen@qt.io>

Patch Set 3:

Now we have docs for clipRect() and boundingRect().  ATM the meaning of clipRect() is a bit more complicated: in 6.3 we have "viewporting" : any item can act as a viewport for its children, but it's opt-in for both the parent and the child; and only in that case, clipRect() calculates the intersection with the clipRect() of the parent that is acting as the viewport, and so on recursively up the parent chain.  So that's not cheap for hit-testing, and maybe this makes less sense now.

I guess that's indeed a lot of code for just a fallback in case of a setup issue (kde plugin not installed or not found).

Surprisingly Allan made some commits to this code in 2017, which means it is/was actually used...
(commit c08dc1e04f4e93016, commit 5e3b284345f0f6c0da7...)

Patch Set 1:

Hmm. I do end up using this whenever I build a new Qt version that I haven't updated KDE for. Especially with Qt6.

Patch Set 1:

It wouldn't ever be useful in a non-kde desktop?

I don't know the history: why was it added to Qt? didn't KDE always ship its own QPlatformTheme?

Better to provide more information what's the best practise for this purpose in KDE world nowadays, thanks.

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> It wouldn't ever be useful in a non-kde desktop?
> 
> I don't know the history: why was it added to Qt? didn't KDE always ship its own QPlatformTheme?

It is only useful for
a) developers
b) applications that ship their on Qt version

The problem is the KDE QPA libs technically use private API and doesn't work with non-system versions of Qt.

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> > Patch Set 1:
> > 
> > It wouldn't ever be useful in a non-kde desktop?
> > 
> > I don't know the history: why was it added to Qt? didn't KDE always ship its own QPlatformTheme?
> 
> It is only useful for
> a) developers
> b) applications that ship their on Qt version
> 
> The problem is the KDE QPA libs technically use private API and doesn't work with non-system versions of Qt.

It is a problem for the non-system Qt versions, but I think it is impossible to include all the desktop environments codes in the Qt source, it is worthwhile to implement QPlatformTheme by the desktop environment self.

Patch Set 1:

Note, the KDE plugins could perhaps be improved. If they didn't use QObjectPrivate, it wouldn't crash Qt applications with a different version. QPA api while private is usually stable, and only QObjectPrivate really enforce exact version match.

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> Note, the KDE plugins could perhaps be improved. If they didn't use QObjectPrivate, it wouldn't crash Qt applications with a different version. QPA api while private is usually stable, and only QObjectPrivate really enforce exact version match.

Good point.  Is that because of missing public API that someone could make the case we really ought to have, or things that need to stay private?

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> > Patch Set 1:
> > 
> > Note, the KDE plugins could perhaps be improved. If they didn't use QObjectPrivate, it wouldn't crash Qt applications with a different version. QPA api while private is usually stable, and only QObjectPrivate really enforce exact version match.
> 
> Good point.  Is that because of missing public API that someone could make the case we really ought to have, or things that need to stay private?

QObjectPrivate is just an optimization. Not sure where it is used though, just know I often need to make sure custom Qt versions doesnt pick up system Qt plugins.

The other problem is the entire QPA api being officially private, which I guess is a policy decision.

Patch Set 1:

> The other problem is the entire QPA api being officially private, which I guess is a policy decision.

System APIs sometimes change without much warning, and Qt's reason to exist is to paper over those; so yeah, being flexible to adapt to change is important, and guaranteeing that QPA won't change would take away some flexibility.  It's good if we change it seldom enough that you have a good chance of compatibility between versions.  We've gone through major architectural shifts the last few years: RHI because there are so many rendering APIs now, Qt 6 and the event refactoring, macOS 11, Windows 11 is imminent, VR is in development (did you know that in OpenXR there is no such thing as a window, so even using QWindow and subclasses is causing some trouble?), trying to get native styling again in Qt Quick Controls... I wouldn't vote for stable QPA API.

Patch Set 1:

So any conclusion yet?  dev branch is 6.4 now.

Patch Set 1:

Needs a few more fixes, and the macOS style has issues, before we can land this

Patch Set 3:

With this change I'm not seeing any graphics artefacts for the fusion or windows styles, but the macOS style has issues. Disabling the scrollbars removes most of them, but there are some minor artefacts at the borders between cells. I suspect this is somehow related to the macOS style drawing the border and/or the scrollbars not fully opaque, so calling table.viewport()->setAttribute(Qt::WA_OpaquePaintEvent, true) is perhaps giving the widgets-code the wrong idea
Patch Set 4: Commit message was updated.

Patch Set 4:

> Disabling the scrollbars removes most of them, but there are some minor artefacts at the borders 
> between cells. I suspect this is somehow related to the macOS style drawing the border and/or the
> scrollbars not fully opaque, so calling table.viewport()->setAttribute(Qt::WA_OpaquePaintEvent, true) > is perhaps giving the widgets-code the wrong idea

Interesting, I disabled mac-style completely (well, by selecting a different one and reducing the number of cells in a test example so that no scrollbars involved at all). Looks like a minor geometry mis-calculation in QTableView. Investigating ....

Interesting, scroll returns bool, so we can detect we attempted to scroll twice but no more image to copy, so return false? Seems to fix a weird row overlap for me in a table view (implementation is very primitive, sure, and also this would probably add some visible 'stuttering'?)

I must admit, that I do not completely understand how my patch fixes the crash, but it seems to be related to the concurrency model.

I'm not sure if it's a Win11 bug or an intentional behavior change, but looks like it requires the MTA model for CoInitializeEx().

Please review!

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> I'm not sure if it's a Win11 bug or an intentional behavior change, but looks like it requires the MTA model for CoInitializeEx().

I tried to reproduce the issue on Windows 10 but failed (I don't have a windows 11 env at hand).

It is difficult to say what might cause this, but would seem to be a behavioral change indeed. What might happen here is that:
1) when we use single-threaded apartment then there are some events still lingering in the Windows message queue (not visible to the API) and they are handled after Co_uninitialize => crash
2) if we change to multi-threaded apartment then there are no hidden message queues and crash does not happen. This will however mean that we are "on our own" as far as COM threading protection is concerned. 

If we do this change I think it is important to double-check that we don't rely on Windows doing the COM access thread protection elsewhere in the code

Patch Set 1:

I think we have to have a look at the usage of CoInitialize(Ex) in Qt in general. We use different initializations in different places (<qtbase>/src/plugins/platforms/windows/qwindowsservices.cpp uses apartment threaded, <qtbase>/src/plugins/platforms/windows/qwindowstheme.cpp and here uses multithreaded). If functionality which use different threading models is used in one thread, won't we run into a fail with RPC_E_CHANGED_MODE on CoInitializeEx? This might not happen in smaller examples and is only partly related to this patch, but something to keep in mind.

Something that is related to the patch: Should we change all CoInitialize(Ex) calls in bluetooth to the same version?

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> Something that is related to the patch: Should we change all CoInitialize(Ex) calls in bluetooth to the same version?

That's something that came into my mind as well. We now have a scenario to reproduce a crash in this case, but other calls to CoInitialize() might crash under some other scenarios. But should it be done together with this patch? Or as a separate one?

The other puzzling thing is that it keeps working (both on Windows 10 and Windows 11) even if I remove the CoInitialize(Ex)/CoUninitialize calls. However I clearly remember adding them because of some COM-method returning a "COM not initialized" error...

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> I think we have to have a look at the usage of CoInitialize(Ex) in Qt in general. We use different initializations in different places (<qtbase>/src/plugins/platforms/windows/qwindowsservices.cpp uses apartment threaded, <qtbase>/src/plugins/platforms/windows/qwindowstheme.cpp and here uses multithreaded). If functionality which use different threading models is used in one thread, won't we run into a fail with RPC_E_CHANGED_MODE on CoInitializeEx? This might not happen in smaller examples and is only partly related to this patch, but something to keep in mind.
> 
> Something that is related to the patch: Should we change all CoInitialize(Ex) calls in bluetooth to the same version?

I actually did some more analysis, and that's what I see in qtbase:
- we use CoInitializeEx() with STA or MTA only when a the code is running in a new thread (this is actually the case for qwindowsservices.cpp and qwindowstheme.cpp). So in that case we would not get an RPC_E_CHANGED_MODE error, because no other code will be running in that threads.
- We use a simple CoInitialize() in all the places where the code can run in main thread (see qfilesystemengine_win.cpp or qnetconnmonitor_win.cpp).

This patch updates the threading model for the code that runs inside its own helper thread, so I'd say it's pretty safe to do this change.
As for the other places in QtBluetooth - qbluetoothdevicediscoveryagent_winrt.cpp and qbluetoothserver_winrt.cpp - they can be executed from the main thread. So I think we should not touch them right now.

Yep I think you are right. Thanks for the investigation. Let's stay aware of this "problem" in the future :)

messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

Please review, more info about the issue in the jira task comments.

Patch Set 1:

Just a quick note I took both patches on the relation chain and sensorsshowcase magnetometer seems to work OK on the iPad (I didn't yet internalize the in-depth root cause for the change)

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Looks good to me. I did a side-by-side comparison with iOS and Android device, and now both point (roughly) to geomagnetic north. This is also in line with the example's documentation.

Before these two patches (in the gerrit relation chain) the magnet icon just stutters in same place on iOS, or will not move at all if the returnGeoValues property is set.
